<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n33245e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n33" href="#n33245e">N33 (VI.B.4)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n33all.htm#n33245e"> 245(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ganglion / brain</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">In a flea, or other insect, the nervous system consists of a chain of ganglia connected by a nervous cord. A <mark>ganglion</mark> is a nerve centre and, in a sense, each <mark>is a brain</mark> which may be likened to the one brain of the vertebrate. We have in the cord of ganglia a series of brains, as it were, running from the head down to the extremity of the abdomen. <small> Harold Russell, <a name="HRTF" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#HRTF"><cite title="source">The Flea</cite></a> (1913) 45</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Ganglion cells (neurones) are a part of the nervous system.</mm> </dd></dl>
